                        <desc>
                        <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iir(ecto) #iiv(erso)" facs="001 002 003">Fols. ir(ecto), iir(ecto), iiv(erso)</locus> scrawls
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e2">
                        <desc>
                          words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#84r #91r #99v #140v #168v" facs="086 093 102 143 171">folss. 84r, 91r, 99v, 140v, 168v, </locus>, etc.);
                          and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#14r #36r #148v #156v" facs="016 038 151 159">14r, 36r, 148v, 156v, </locus>);
                          and in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#148r" facs="150"> f. 148r, line 2</locus>);
                          erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#107v #108v #120r #124r" facs="110 111 122 126">107v, 108v, 120r, 124r, </locus>, etc.);
                          text has been removed (e.g., <locus target="#17v #108r" facs="020 110">17v, 108r</locus>, )
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e3">
                        <desc>
                          The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line.
                          Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                          appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate
                          script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe
                          completes the line of text above or below the end of the line
                          (throughout). This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of
                          lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#5r #6v #7r #7v" facs="007 009 010">fols. 5r, 6v, 7r, 7v</locus>)
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                    </list>
